 ---
description: General coding workflow standards
alwaysApply: true
---

# Working Style

- Favor a brownfield workflow: plan briefly, implement a small concrete change, review the code, then refine.
- Do not over-design up front unless explicitly requested.
- Prefer small, inspectable steps over large rewrites.
- Preserve working behavior unless the task explicitly calls for restructuring.

# Code Quality

- Keep code easy for a human to read and review.
- Prefer simple, explicit code over clever abstractions.
- Extract helper functions when they improve reuse or clarity.
- Avoid deeply nested conditionals when a clearer structure is possible.
- Avoid mutating shared state in ways that make behavior hard to trace.

# Architecture
- When a library wraps or serializes another (e.g. UI framework + widget bridge + rendering backend), treat the combination as one versioned stack. Changing one package without checking the others is a first-class risk.
-Prefer explicit pins for packages that sit on compatibility boundaries (major upgrades, optional extras, or packages that compile against a specific ABI/API). Open-ended lower bounds alone are not enough unless CI or a lockfile proves compatibility.
-Prefer the documented integration path (official decorator/output pair, adapter, or plugin) over ad hoc mixing of APIs that “look similar.”
-When debugging “code looks correct but nothing shows / wrong state,” check dependency and API mismatch before refactoring application logic.
- Separate data preparation, business logic, and UI/rendering when relevant.
- Do not mix expensive preprocessing into interactive or frequently rerun paths if it can be done once upstream.
- Match the existing project structure unless there is a strong reason to change it.

# Collaboration

- When requirements are incomplete, implement the smallest sensible version first instead of inventing a large system.
- If a task reveals repeated confusion or a recurring mistake, suggest a new rule that can be added here.
- Prefer concrete progress over speculative architecture.
- If I suggest anything that is incongruent or contradictory to existing functions or data in the codebase, point it out in your output

# Verification

- After making changes, suggest the smallest meaningful way to verify them.
- For UI changes, describe what to check manually.
- For logic changes, prefer lightweight checks or tests when appropriate.